<s> The path part is absolute if it starts with a "/".  </s>
<s> In your last example "/../blah" is an absolute path because it assumes a root starting place while "../blah" is relative to wherever you happen to be.  </s>
<s> Any complete "//" type URI, that is, one with "scheme://" in it, has to be absolute because the path part starts with a "/" and the root is defined by the stuff before that "/".  </s>
<s> So in your last example, "http://www.w3.org" defines a root (probably as part of the configuration of that http server) and "/../blah" navigates from that root.  </s>
<s> It is absolute because it is indpendent of the context ("web page") where this URL occurs.  </s>
